1 Load packages

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(startR) #custom functions
  library(lubridate) #handle dates
  library(here) #path management
  library(rnaturalearth) #coastlines and basemaps
  library(raster) #work with the NC file
  library(tidyverse) #data management
})

2 The data

Fir temperature data, weâll use GHCN_CAMS Gridded 2m Temperature, which provides âMonthly means from 1948 to Jul 2019â, using a â0.5 degree latitude x 0.5 degree longitude global grid (360x720)â.

These data are already on a 0.5 degree resolution, so thereâs no downscaling needed. We will just crop the extent, rotate the rasters, mask by chile, and create a panel.

2.1 Load the data

temp <- brick(here("raw_data", "air_temp.nc"))

2.2 Preview the data

Letâs take a look at the first 12 months of data on each raster. The title in each plot contains the date.

plot(temp[[1:12]])

Figure 2.1: First 12 months of data in the high resolution raster

3 Modifications

The figure above show global temperature over land. But we are only interested in Chile. In order to better manage the data, we must crop these rasters to the extent (boundign box) of Chile. Letâs get a shapefile for Chile.

3.1 Chilean boundary

The rnaturalearth package contains a repository of different political boundaries of interest. We can retrieve Chileâs shapefile with the following lines.

# Load chile boundaries
chl <- ne_countries(scale = "medium", country = "Chile", returnclass = "sp")

The above retrieves the Chilean boundary shown below, which has a medium resolution. A high resolution is a bit problematic, because of the intricate coastline in the south.

plot(chl)

Figure 3.1: Chilean boundarie from rnaturalearth

3.2 Modify extent

Figures 2.1 shows how the data are global and that longitude goes from 0 to 360. Letâs fix that first by cropping down to the extent of Chile, rotating the rasters, and then masking it by Chile.

# Get Chile's extent and "rotate" its longitude
chl_extent <- extent(chl) + c(360, 360, 0, 0)

# Reduce size to extent of chile
temp_ext <- crop(temp, y = chl_extent)

The rasters are now cropped to Chileâs extent.

plot(temp_ext[[1]])

Figure 3.2: First month of temperature for Chile

3.3 Convert units

Note that the colorbar indicates temperatures from 260 to 300. This is because it is in Kelvin. Letâs convert the data to celsius.

# Convert units
temp_cel <- temp_ext -273.15
plot(temp_cel[[1]])

Figure 3.3: FData converted to celsius

3.4 Rotate to -180 to 180

# Rotate the raster
temp_rot <- rotate(temp_cel)
plot(temp_rot[[1]])
plot(chl, add = T)

3.5 Crop to Chile

The above figures show all data in the extent, but we want them for cells that are within Chile only. We first reduce the extent because itâs an operation that collects cells within 4 points (the bounding box). Now that we have less data, we can use a more intricate shape to extract the data. In this case, Chileâs boundary.

temp_chl <- mask(temp_rot, chl)
writeRaster(x = temp_chl,
            filename = here("data", "temperature_raster_chile.tif"))
plot(temp_chl[[1]])
plot(chl, add = T)

4 Finalize the data

4.1 Convert to a data.frame

temp_df <- raster::as.data.frame(temp_chl, xy = T) %>% 
  gather(date, temp, -c(x, y)) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(date = str_remove(date, "X")) %>% 
  separate(date, sep = "\\.", into = c("year", "month", "day", "hour", "minute", "second")) %>% 
  mutate(date = date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-"))) %>% 
  select(lon = x, lat = y, year, month, day, date, temp)
head(temp_df)

4.2 Export the resulting data

write.csv(x = temp_df,
          file = here("data", "temperature_panel.csv"),
          row.names = F)

4.3 Further inspection

temp_df %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarize(temp = mean(temp, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = temp)) +
  geom_line() +
  ggtheme_plot()

Figure 4.1: Time series of surface temperature in chile.
